title: For Sale:  Warne Tactical Scope Mounts
postcontent:
Two available for 1" Scope

$120 Each


Finally a mounting platform designed for the serious shooting enthusiast and professionals world wide!

The all new WARNE Rapid Acquisition Multi-Sight Platform, or RAMP, is a cantilever style scope mounting platform that allows proper scope installation on the popular AR-15 rifle. By design, the AR platform was intended for fixed iron sights and did not offer an acceptable mounting surface for optics. As the weapon system evolved from the military designate M16A1 to the M16A3 and M4, Picatinny mounting systems became standard equipment, however, the rail system found on the A3 and M4 weapon systems still did not allow a variable power optic to be mounted far enough forward with conventional scope mounts.

The new Warne RAMP modular mounting system positions the front ring forward of the upper receiver by 1 3/4” allowing the optics to be mounted farther forward allowing the shooter to position their head in the proper position whether upright or prone and not sacrifice their shooting position due to improper optic positioning.

The new Warne RAMP also offers unique 45 degree mounting rails on one or both sides of the optic. As you know, variable power optics are great for distance but not CQB scenarios. Additionally, CQB sights are great for close quarters and entry scenarios but not for distance shots or target ID. So which one do you choose? Why not have both? The R.A.M.P provides exactly that. The primary sight can be as small as a 1-4 or as large as an 8.5-25 or larger variable power optic. With a mini red dot on one or both sides of the ocular, a shooter can transition from scope to dot or dot to scope in less than a second by rotating the weapon 45 degrees left or right. While the technique is not new, the position of the red dot is. By placing the sight under the ocular of the scope, we have provided a wider field of view thru the mini red dot and make acquiring the dot in the sight faster than you can imagine. And once again, you won’t have to sacrifice your shooting position when transitioning from sight to sight.

FEATURES:

    6000 Series Aluminum
    #8 Torx style fasteners with steel threaded inserts
    Cantilever design for proper eye relief
    Dual 45 degree mounting rails (with the option to remove one or both) for quick transition between scope and red dot
    1/2″ tactical nut attachment, 65 in/lb of torque is recommended

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Gold Half Eagle $5 Coin
postcontent:
The Half Eagle is a 5 dollar gold coin produced by the United States Mint from 1795 to 1929. The half eagle was the first gold coin actually struck for the United States.

This is a 1913p Indian Head Half Eagle ($5) Its in pretty good condition, theres still a lot of definition in the head and the reverse side eagle. the only problem is a mis-shaped star, one of the 13. Rated at MS62. This is your chance to own a part of american history, the fist gold coin from a US mint! Kinda sad to see this one go, but its time. Open to offers and trades. 
Thanks. 

Coin Facts
Bela Lyon Pratt’s $5 Indian Head Half Eagle Gold Coin design replaced Christian Gobrecht’s Liberty Head design which had been used since 1839. Minted between 1908 and 1929, Pratt’s design (shared with the $2.50 “Quarter Eagle”) was unique in US coinage history for using the unusual “incuse relief” style, according to the wishes of President Theodore Roosevelt. The obverse of the coin features an American Indian in war bonnet. The word LIBERTY across the top edge of the coin divides the thirteen stars draped across the upper portion of the coin, and the date is found below the bust. The reverse features a standing bald eagle atop a bundle of arrows wrapped in an olive branch. Compared to the $10 Gold Eagle, the two mottos on the reverse of the Half Eagle are switched: “E Pluribus Unum” appears on the left, with “In God We Trust” on the right.


Have any question regarding this item please feel free to contact me.

I also have a few Silver Dollars, Silver Bouillon and some other collectible coins. Send me an email if you interested. Thanks for looking.

I can also take Major Credit Cards and Paypal and ship this item if your not local.

title: For Sale:   U.S. Springfield Armory M1903 Springfield 1922 Mfr
postcontent:
.30-06 Cal, Serial number 12468xx puts it as a 1922 Manufacture rifle. Barrel Stamped 4-22 (April 1922)

- Good Looking gun.
- Superb action.
- B&M Belding & Mull bolt sleeve peep sight for the Model 1903 Springfield rifle. These sights were carried in the B&M catalog in the mid 1920's and were very expensive for the time. There was a great desire at the tome to move the rear sight as far back as possible to increase accuracy and target acquisition. This sight is adjustable for both windage and elevation.  It also has its own side mounted safety lever, since mounting it required removing the original wing safety. 
- Very very nice shiny bore.
- Stock has been modified in the grip area to add a bit of a pistol grip, I suppose.  Added wood is also walnut with similar grain.
- Heavy steel buttplate, see photos.

Send best offers. Must be sold by the 17th, back to school.  If the ad is up the rifle is for sale.  

I have other pictures as well.  I took these pictures the day I opened up the collection, and have since done a light cleaning and oiling.
